### **Splunk**

#### GUI

#### Files

24. [Inputs.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/latest/admin/inputsconf)  
    1. File to specify where the data will grab from  
       1. \[splunktcp://\<port\>\] (incoming splunk data, from splunk-based forwarder)  
       2. \[tcp(udp)://\<port\>\] (incoming tcp/udp data)  
       3. \[tcp(udp)-ssl://\<port\>\] (incoming encrypted traffic. Requires an SSL.pem and password)  
25. [Outputs.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/latest/admin/outputsconf)  
    1. File where to send data to  
    2. Must be configured on forwarders  
26. [Props.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/latest/admin/propsconf)  
    1. File to generate additional fields from existing field data (calculated), alias data, call transforms  
    2. Forwarders and ingestion point must have identical copies of file  
    3. calls:  
       1. EVAL-  
       2. ALIAS-  
       3. TRANSFORMS-  
27. [Transforms.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/latest/admin/transformsconf)  
    1. File to use regex and metadata to scan data for new (extracted) fields  
    2. Forwarders and ingestion point must have identical copies of file  
28. [Limits.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/latest/admin/limitsconf)  
    1. File to change splunk resource usage  
       1. \[thruput\] maxKBps \= 0 (removes limit on ingestion/forwarding)  
29. [Server.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/latest/admin/serverconf)  
    1. File to configure splunk instance  
    2. Can change hostname, clustering, management, etc. here  
30. [Deploymentclient.conf](https://docs.splunk.com/Documentation/Splunk/latest/admin/deploymentclientconf)  
    1. File to configure splunk universal forwarder

#### Machines

38. **Manager (Cluster)**: The **boss** of the indexers, making sure they work together and share data properly.  
39. **Indexer(s)**: The **big library** that stores and organizes all the logs so you can find them later.  
40. **Search Head(s)**: The **detective** that looks through all the stored logs and finds answers when you ask questions.  
41. **Captain**: The **leader of the search heads**, making sure they don’t fight and work together as a team.  
42. **Deployer**: The **teacher** that gives instructions to search heads in a cluster so they all know what to do.  
43. **Deployment Server**: The **mailman** that delivers new tools and updates to smaller Splunk helpers like forwarders.  
44. **Heavy Forwarder**: A **smart messenger** that can read and filter logs before sending them to the indexers.

#### Ports

| Port | Protocol | Used By | Purpose |
| ----- | ----- | ----- | ----- |
| **8000** | HTTP(S) | Splunk Web UI | Web interface for users to access Splunk. |
| **8089** | HTTPS | Splunk Management Port | Used for Splunk REST API and internal communication between Splunk instances. |
| **9997** | TCP | Indexers | Default port for receiving **forwarded** data from Universal or Heavy Forwarders. |
| **8191** | TCP | KV Store | Splunk's **Key-Value Store** (MongoDB-based). |
| **9200** | HTTP | Splunk ES | Used for **Splunk Enterprise Security (ES) Threat Intelligence downloads**. |
| **9998** | TCP | Splunk Indexer Clustering | Communication between Indexers in a cluster. |
| **17000** | TCP | Search Head Cluster | Used for **SHC captain election** and synchronization. |

#### Troubleshooting

1. Check Real-Time Logs for Issues

| tail \-f $SPLUNK\_HOME/var/log/splunk/splunkd.log | grep \-E "ERROR|WARN|FATAL" |
| :---- |

This captures **errors, warnings, and fatal issues** at once.

2\. Check Indexer Connection Issues

| splunk list forward-server |
| :---- |

* Verifies if **forwarders are connected** to indexers.

  3\. Verify Data Inputs Are Active

| splunk list monitor |
| :---- |


* Lists all **monitored** log files to ensure they are being ingested.

  4\. Check Search Head Cluster Status

| splunk show shcluster-status |
| :---- |


* Helps **identify sync issues** among search heads.

  5\. Check Disk Space Issues (Splunk May Stop Ingesting)

| df \-h | grep splunk |
| :---- |


* Ensures **sufficient disk space** for logs.

  6\. Check Running Processes (Splunk Daemon)

| ps aux | grep splunk |
| :---- |


* Verifies that **Splunk services are running**.

  7\. Restart Splunk If Needed (Safely)

| splunk stopsplunk start |
| :---- |


* Safely restarts Splunk after changes.

  8\. Test If Splunk Web and REST API Are Responding

| curl \-k https://localhost:8089/services/server/info \-u admin:\<password\> |
| :---- |


* Confirms if **Splunk’s API is responsive**.

  9\. Check Splunk’s Port Usage

| netstat \-tulnp | grep splunk |
| :---- |


* Ensures required **ports (8000, 8089, 9997, etc.)** are open.

  10\. Find Licensing Issues

| splunk list licenser-pools |
| :---- |


* Checks if Splunk **exceeded its license**.

  11\. Investigate Why an App Isn’t Loading

| tail \-f $SPLUNK\_HOME/var/log/splunk/python.log |
| :---- |


* Debugs **Python-based Splunk apps**.

  12\. Check Indexing Rate (Ingest Performance)

| splunk query 'index=\_internal source=\*metrics.log group=per\_index\_thruput | stats sum(kb) by series' |
| :---- |


* Shows **how much data is getting indexed**.
